net.sf.mmm.util.contenttype.api

Interface ContentType

  • All Superinterfaces:
    GenericTreeNode<ContentType,ContentType>, Node<ContentType>, TreeNode<ContentType>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    ContentTypeBean

    public interface ContentType
extends TreeNode<ContentType>
    A ContentType represents the type of some content (typically a file or BLOB). A ContentType is similar to a mimetype but more fine-grained (there can be multiple ContentTypes for a single mimetype) and well structured in a hierarchy-tree.
    Author:
    Joerg Hohwiller (hohwille at users.sourceforge.net)

    • Method Detail

      • getId

        String getId()
        This method gets the technical name of this ContentType. For displaying the ContentType (to the end-user) you should use the title instead. However the title of a ContentType may change over the time while the ID will NOT. Therefore you may use this method for internal decisions.
        Returns:
        the ID of this ContentType (e.g. "PNG").

      • getTitle

        String getTitle()
        This method gets the display name of this ContentType (e.g. "Portable-Network-Graphics")
        Returns:
        the common type-name.

      • getDefaultExtension

        String getDefaultExtension()
        This method gets the default extension associated with this ContentType (e.g. ".jpg").
        Returns:
        the default file-extension or null if not defined.

      • getExtensions

        Collection<String> getExtensions()
        This method gets the list of all extensions associated with this ContentType including the default extension (e.g. contains ".jpg" and ".jpeg").
        Returns:
        a Collection of all additional file-extensions.

      • getMimetype

        String getMimetype()
        This method gets the mimetype of this ContentType (e.g. "image/png").
        Returns:
        the mimetype string.

      • isAbstract

        boolean isAbstract()
        This method determines if the current ContentType is abstract. If concrete data has an exact ContentType that ContentType should NOT be abstract.
        An abstract ContentType should have sub-types, a non abstract ContentType can have sub-types.
        Returns:
        true if the ContentType is abstract, false otherwise.

      • getTechnicalParent

        ContentType getTechnicalParent()
        This method gets the technical parent of this ContentType as node.
        While the ContentType as node represents the logical hierarchy of ContentTypes, the technical parent gives the technical view on the hierarchy.
        There is no getTechnicalChildren() method. The children are always retrieved via GenericTreeNode.getChildren(). Therefore a ContentType can have children that have it as technical parent while GenericTreeNode.getParent() returns another ContentType.
        For instance the logical parent of the type ODT (Open Document Text) is the type office document. From a technical point of view an ODT-file is a ZIP-file with a specific structure. Therefore the technical parent is the type ZIP .
        Typically end-users will NOT be interested in the technical view. However it is exposed for those that may find it useful.
        Returns:
        the technical parent of this ContentType or null if this is the technical root node.

      • isTechnicalAncestor

        boolean isTechnicalAncestor(ContentType technicalType)
        This method determines if this ContentType is an ancestor of the given technicalType. In other words this method checks if this ContentType is the direct or indirect technical parent of the given technicalType.
        Parameters:
        technicalType - is the ContentType to check.
        Returns:
        true if this ContentType is a technical ancestor of the given technicalType.
        See Also:
        GenericTreeNode.isAncestor(net.sf.mmm.util.collection.api.GenericTreeNode)
